******
[2]
Date: Thu 25 Dec 2014
Source: The Washington Post [edited]
http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/to-your-health/wp/2014/12/25/missouri-company-recalls-caramel-apples-that-may-be-linked-to-listeria-outbreak/


A Missouri company is recalling packaged caramel apples that may be linked to a [listeriosis] outbreak that has hospitalized 29 people and killed at least 3 in 10 states. Happy Apples of Washington, Missouri, recalled caramel apples carrying a best-use date between [25 Aug 2014] and [23 Nov 2014] that were sold in grocery, discount, and club stores in packs of one, 3, 4, and 8. In a statement issued on Wednesday [24 Dec 1024], the company said an apple supplier, Bidart Brothers, had notified it that "there may be a connection between this outbreak and the apples that they supplied" to a Happy Apples facility in California.

On Friday [19 Dec 2014], the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention warned consumers to stop eating prepackaged caramel apples while it investigated the outbreak [due to] _Listeria monocytogenes_, a bacterium that causes the rare but sometimes fatal infection [listeriosis]. Older people, pregnant women, newborns, and people with weakened immune systems are particularly vulnerable to the pathogen. CDC said 9 of the illnesses occurred in pregnant women or newborns. 3 people have come down with meningitis.

In 2011, listeria in cantaloupes killed 33 people and sickened 147 in 28 states, according to CDC. In the current outbreak, no illnesses have been associated with uncoated apples or caramel candy, or with caramel apples that are not prepackaged, the agency said.

CDC originally linked the bacteria to 5 deaths, but the Food and Drug Administration, in an update posted on Thursday [25 Dec 2014], said only 3 deaths can be attributed to listeria. It is unclear whether a 4th death is connected to listeria, the FDA said, and the 5th was not caused by the organism.

On Monday [22 Dec 2014], Seattle food safety attorney Bill Marler filed a wrongful death lawsuit against the Safeway grocery store chain over the death of 81 year old, who, Marler stated, bought a caramel apple shortly before Halloween and died [2 Dec 2014]. Listeriosis was the cause of death, according to the statement, which cited [the patient's] family. Safeway later pulled the caramel apples from its shelves.

Health officials still have not determined the location of the listeria contamination.

Happy Apples said the caramel apples were available in Alabama, Arizona, Arkansas, California, Colorado, Florida, Georgia, Hawaii, Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Louisiana, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Mississippi, Missouri, Montana, Nebraska, Nevada, New Mexico, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Tennessee, Texas, Utah, Washington, and Wisconsin. The company ceased production of them at the end of October [2014]. They are no longer available in stores.

[byline: Lenny Bernstein]

